134→- [ ] `InMemoryEventBus` implements `EventBus` without TypeScript errors
135→- [ ] `EventEnvelope.id` is a `string`, not `uuid` Drizzle type — this is plain TypeScript
136→
137→**Edge Cases**:
138→- `EventHandler` returns `Promise<void>`. Bus implementations must not swallow errors — use `try/catch` around handler invocation and emit an error event or log.
139→
140→---
141→
142→### T009: Implement PgNotifyBus (`src/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.ts`)
143→
144→**Purpose**: Production event bus using PostgreSQL LISTEN/NOTIFY for wake-up and `trigger_events` table for durable queuing. Handles reconnection on connection loss.
145→
146→**Steps**:
147→1. Create `src/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.ts`
148→2. On construction, acquire a dedicated `pg.Client` (not from pool) and call `LISTEN pipelines_events`
149→3. On `publish`: INSERT into `trigger_events`, then send `NOTIFY pipelines_events, '<event_id>'`
150→4. On `notification` event from the pg client: fetch the full event from `trigger_events`, dispatch to matching handlers, mark `processed_at`
151→5. Implement reconnect: on client `error` or `end`, wait 2s and re-establish the LISTEN connection
152→
153→```typescript
154→// src/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.ts
155→import { Client } from 'pg';
156→import { eq, isNull } from 'drizzle-orm';
157→import type { NodePgDatabase } from 'drizzle-orm/node-postgres';
158→import { triggerEvents } from '../schema';
159→import type { EventBus, EventEnvelope, EventHandler } from './interface';
160→import type { TriggerType } from '../types';
161→
162→const NOTIFY_CHANNEL = 'pipelines_events';
163→const RECONNECT_DELAY_MS = 2000;
164→
165→export class PgNotifyBus implements EventBus {
166→  private handlers = new Map<TriggerType, Map<string, EventHandler>>();
167→  private listenClient: Client | null = null;
168→  private subscriptionCounter = 0;
169→  private closed = false;
170→
171→  constructor(
172→    private readonly db: NodePgDatabase<Record<string, unknown>>,
173→    private readonly connectionString: string,
174→  ) {}
175→
176→  async start(): Promise<void> {
177→    await this.connect();
178→  }
179→
180→  private async connect(): Promise<void> {
181→    if (this.closed) return;
182→    const client = new Client({ connectionString: this.connectionString });
183→    client.on('error', (err) => {
184→      console.error('[PgNotifyBus] LISTEN client error:', err.message);
185→      this.scheduleReconnect();
186→    });
187→    client.on('end', () => {
188→      if (!this.closed) this.scheduleReconnect();
189→    });
190→    client.on('notification', (msg) => {
191→      if (msg.channel === NOTIFY_CHANNEL && msg.payload) {
192→        void this.handleNotification(msg.payload);
193→      }
194→    });
195→    await client.connect();
196→    await client.query(`LISTEN ${NOTIFY_CHANNEL}`);
197→    this.listenClient = client;
198→  }
199→
200→  private scheduleReconnect(): void {
201→    setTimeout(() => void this.connect(), RECONNECT_DELAY_MS);
202→  }
203→
204→  private async handleNotification(eventId: string): Promise<void> {
205→    // Fetch the full event from the DB queue
206→    const rows = await this.db
207→      .select()
208→      .from(triggerEvents)
209→      .where(eq(triggerEvents.id, eventId));
210→
211→    if (rows.length === 0) return;
212→    const row = rows[0];
213→
214→    // Mark as processed first (at-least-once delivery — idempotent handlers required)
215→    await this.db
216→      .update(triggerEvents)
217→      .set({ processedAt: new Date() })
218→      .where(eq(triggerEvents.id, eventId));
219→
220→    const envelope: EventEnvelope = {
221→      id: row.id,
222→      tenantId: row.tenantId,
223→      eventType: row.eventType as TriggerType,
224→      payload: row.payload as Record<string, unknown>,
225→      createdAt: row.createdAt,
226→    };
227→
228→    const subs = this.handlers.get(envelope.eventType);
229→    if (!subs) return;
230→
231→    for (const handler of subs.values()) {
232→      try {
233→        await handler(envelope);
234→      } catch (err) {
235→        console.error('[PgNotifyBus] Handler error for event', eventId, err);
236→      }
237→    }
238→  }
239→
240→  async publish(
241→    tenantId: string,
242→    eventType: TriggerType,
243→    payload: Record<string, unknown>,
244→  ): Promise<string> {
245→    const [row] = await this.db
246→      .insert(triggerEvents)
247→      .values({ tenantId, eventType, payload })
248→      .returning({ id: triggerEvents.id });
249→
250→    // NOTIFY payload is just the event ID — stays well under 8000-byte limit
251→    await this.db.execute(
252→      sql`SELECT pg_notify(${NOTIFY_CHANNEL}, ${row.id})`
253→    );
254→
255→    return row.id;
256→  }
257→
258→  subscribe(eventType: TriggerType, handler: EventHandler): string {
259→    if (!this.handlers.has(eventType)) this.handlers.set(eventType, new Map());
260→    const id = `sub-${++this.subscriptionCounter}`;
261→    this.handlers.get(eventType)!.set(id, handler);
262→    return id;
263→  }
264→
265→  unsubscribe(subscriptionId: string): void {
266→    for (const subs of this.handlers.values()) {
267→      subs.delete(subscriptionId);
268→    }
269→  }
270→
271→  async close(): Promise<void> {
272→    this.closed = true;
273→    if (this.listenClient) {
274→      await this.listenClient.end();
275→      this.listenClient = null;
276→    }
277→  }
278→}
279→```
280→
281→**Files**:
282→- `src/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.ts` (new, ~95 lines)
283→
284→**Validation**:
285→- [ ] `tsc --noEmit` passes on `pg-notify-bus.ts`
286→- [ ] `PgNotifyBus` implements `EventBus` interface without TypeScript errors
287→- [ ] `LISTEN` call uses the `NOTIFY_CHANNEL` constant, not a hardcoded string
288→- [ ] `publish` inserts into `trigger_events` before sending `pg_notify`
289→- [ ] `handleNotification` marks `processed_at` before dispatching to handlers
290→
291→**Edge Cases**:
292→- `pg.Client` vs pool: The LISTEN client must be a standalone `Client` — using a pool connection will break because the pool recycles connections. Do not use `db` (the Drizzle pool) for LISTEN.
293→- At-least-once delivery: if the server restarts between NOTIFY and `handleNotification`, the event stays in `trigger_events` with `processed_at = null`. The executor's poll loop (WP04) recovers unprocessed events on startup.
294→- The `sql` template tag for `pg_notify` must be imported from `drizzle-orm`.
295→
296→---
297→
298→### T010: Create bus factory and barrel export (`src/pipelines/event-bus/index.ts`)
299→
300→**Purpose**: Provide a factory function that returns the correct `EventBus` implementation based on environment, and re-export all public types.
301→
302→**Steps**:
303→1. Create `src/pipelines/event-bus/index.ts`
304→2. Export `createEventBus` factory: returns `PgNotifyBus` in production, `InMemoryEventBus` in test
305→3. Re-export `EventBus`, `EventEnvelope`, `EventHandler`, `InMemoryEventBus`
306→
307→```typescript
308→// src/pipelines/event-bus/index.ts
309→export type { EventBus, EventEnvelope, EventHandler } from './interface';
310→export { InMemoryEventBus } from './interface';
311→export { PgNotifyBus } from './pg-notify-bus';
312→
313→import type { NodePgDatabase } from 'drizzle-orm/node-postgres';
314→import { PgNotifyBus } from './pg-notify-bus';
315→import { InMemoryEventBus } from './interface';
316→import type { EventBus } from './interface';
317→
318→export function createEventBus(
319→  db: NodePgDatabase<Record<string, unknown>>,
320→  connectionString: string,
321→  options?: { useInMemory?: boolean },
322→): EventBus {
323→  if (options?.useInMemory || process.env.NODE_ENV === 'test') {
324→    return new InMemoryEventBus();
325→  }
326→  const bus = new PgNotifyBus(db, connectionString);
327→  // Caller is responsible for calling bus.start() before use
328→  return bus;
329→}
330→```
331→
332→**Files**:
333→- `src/pipelines/event-bus/index.ts` (new, ~25 lines)
334→
335→**Validation**:
336→- [ ] `createEventBus(db, connStr, { useInMemory: true })` returns `InMemoryEventBus` instance
337→- [ ] `createEventBus(db, connStr)` returns `PgNotifyBus` when `NODE_ENV !== 'test'`
338→- [ ] All types re-exported from `index.ts` are accessible via `import { EventBus } from '../event-bus'`
339→
340→**Edge Cases**:
341→- `createEventBus` returns `EventBus` interface, not concrete type. Callers should not cast to `PgNotifyBus` — if they need to call `.start()`, accept it as `PgNotifyBus` explicitly or add `start()` to the `EventBus` interface.
342→
343→---
344→
345→### T011: Unit tests for PgNotifyBus (`tests/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.test.ts`)
346→
347→**Purpose**: Verify `PgNotifyBus` behavior — publish persists to DB, subscribe/unsubscribe works, handler is called after notification, handler errors do not crash the bus.
348→
349→**Steps**:
350→1. Create `tests/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.test.ts`
351→2. Use `InMemoryEventBus` for the majority of tests (no DB required)
352→3. For DB-dependent tests, use the project's test database setup (check existing integration tests for the pattern)
353→4. Test: `publish` returns a string ID
354→5. Test: `subscribe` adds a handler, `unsubscribe` removes it
355→6. Test: published event calls matching handler
356→7. Test: event type mismatch — handler not called for wrong event type
357→8. Test: handler throwing does not prevent other handlers from being called
358→9. Test: `InMemoryEventBus.close()` clears all subscriptions
359→
360→```typescript
361→// tests/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.test.ts
362→import { describe, it, expect, vi } from 'vitest';
363→import { InMemoryEventBus } from '../../../src/pipelines/event-bus';
364→import type { EventEnvelope } from '../../../src/pipelines/event-bus';
365→
366→describe('InMemoryEventBus', () => {
367→  it('publish returns an event id', async () => {
368→    const bus = new InMemoryEventBus();
369→    const id = await bus.publish('tenant-1', 'manual', {});
370→    expect(typeof id).toBe('string');
371→    expect(id.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);
372→  });
373→
374→  it('calls subscribed handler on matching event type', async () => {
375→    const bus = new InMemoryEventBus();
376→    const handler = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined);
377→    bus.subscribe('manual', handler);
378→    await bus.publish('tenant-1', 'manual', { key: 'value' });
379→    expect(handler).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
380→    const envelope = handler.mock.calls[0][0] as EventEnvelope;
381→    expect(envelope.tenantId).toBe('tenant-1');
382→    expect(envelope.eventType).toBe('manual');
383→    expect(envelope.payload).toEqual({ key: 'value' });
384→  });
385→
386→  it('does not call handler for a different event type', async () => {
387→    const bus = new InMemoryEventBus();
388→    const handler = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined);
389→    bus.subscribe('schedule', handler);
390→    await bus.publish('tenant-1', 'manual', {});
391→    expect(handler).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
392→  });
393→
394→  it('unsubscribe removes the handler', async () => {
395→    const bus = new InMemoryEventBus();
396→    const handler = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined);
397→    const subId = bus.subscribe('manual', handler);
398→    bus.unsubscribe(subId);
399→    await bus.publish('tenant-1', 'manual', {});
400→    expect(handler).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
401→  });
402→
403→  it('handler error does not prevent other handlers from being called', async () => {
404→    const bus = new InMemoryEventBus();
405→    const errorHandler = vi.fn().mockRejectedValue(new Error('boom'));
406→    const okHandler = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined);
407→    bus.subscribe('manual', errorHandler);
408→    bus.subscribe('manual', okHandler);
409→    // InMemoryEventBus does not catch errors — document this behavior in test
410→    await expect(bus.publish('tenant-1', 'manual', {})).rejects.toThrow('boom');
411→    // Note: PgNotifyBus wraps each handler in try/catch; InMemoryEventBus does not.
412→    // This test documents the behavioral difference.
413→  });
414→
415→  it('close clears all subscriptions', async () => {
416→    const bus = new InMemoryEventBus();
417→    const handler = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined);
418→    bus.subscribe('manual', handler);
419→    await bus.close();
420→    await bus.publish('tenant-1', 'manual', {});
421→    expect(handler).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
422→  });
423→});
424→```
425→
426→**Files**:
427→- `tests/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.test.ts` (new, ~65 lines)
428→
429→**Validation**:
430→- [ ] `npm test tests/pipelines/event-bus/` exits 0 with all tests passing
431→- [ ] Tests cover: publish, subscribe, unsubscribe, type mismatch, close
432→- [ ] No real database connection needed for unit tests — `InMemoryEventBus` only
433→
434→**Edge Cases**:
435→- The error-handler test documents a known behavioral difference between `InMemoryEventBus` (propagates errors) and `PgNotifyBus` (catches errors per handler). This asymmetry is intentional — tests use InMemoryEventBus for simplicity, production needs resilience.
436→- If the project uses a global test database setup file (e.g., `tests/setup.ts`), import it in integration test files. Do not duplicate DB setup logic.
437→
438→---
439→
440→## Definition of Done
441→
442→- [ ] `src/pipelines/event-bus/interface.ts` — `EventBus`, `EventEnvelope`, `EventHandler`, `InMemoryEventBus`
443→- [ ] `src/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.ts` — `PgNotifyBus` with LISTEN/NOTIFY + queue table
444→- [ ] `src/pipelines/event-bus/index.ts` — factory and barrel exports
445→- [ ] `tests/pipelines/event-bus/pg-notify-bus.test.ts` — unit tests passing
446→- [ ] `npm run typecheck` exits 0
447→- [ ] `npm test` exits 0 with no regressions
448→
449→## Risks
450→
451→- **LISTEN connection loss**: If the PostgreSQL connection drops (network glitch, server restart), NOTIFY events will be missed. The recovery path is the poll loop in WP04 scanning `trigger_events WHERE processed_at IS NULL`. The reconnect logic in `PgNotifyBus` covers transient failures.
452→- **8000-byte NOTIFY limit**: Passing only the event ID in the NOTIFY payload (not the full event) is the correct pattern. If someone changes `publish` to pass the full payload, large events will silently truncate.
453→- **pg vs pg-pool**: Using `pg.Client` directly for LISTEN means the developer must manage connection lifecycle. Ensure `close()` is called during graceful shutdown to avoid hanging processes.
454→
455→## Reviewer Guidance
456→
457→- Verify the LISTEN client is `new Client(...)` from `pg`, not a connection from the Drizzle pool — this is the most common mistake with NOTIFY implementations.
458→- Check that `handleNotification` marks `processed_at` before calling handlers (at-least-once, not exactly-once). If the process crashes after marking but before the handler runs, the event is lost. This tradeoff is acceptable for this use case.
459→- Confirm `publish` uses a transaction if NOTIFY must be atomic with the INSERT — if the INSERT succeeds but NOTIFY fails, the event is still in the queue and will be picked up by the poll loop.
460→

